---
import { links } from '../config';

// Card grid, in the autoloops shape. This is where the four old prose sections
// (Stepper, Invariants, Outputs, WhyOpen) went: one card each for the two
// invariants, one for the docs-first loop, one for propagation, one for what
// lands on disk, one for the open stack. Copy is lifted from those sections
// rather than rewritten, so nothing here promises more than the CLI does.
const features = [
  {
    title: 'Starts from the docs',
    body: 'Every decision lives in the design docs, so the agent knows the whole design, not just the part in front of it.',
  },
  {
    title: 'Nothing starts without a spec',
    body: 'The agent cannot touch a design file until a validated change proposal exists. The edit tools stay locked until it passes.',
  },
  {
    title: 'Nothing is done until the tools agree',
    body: 'Every change is followed by ERC on the schematic and DRC on the board. Violations get read, fixed, and re-run.',
  },
  {
    title: 'Changes propagate',
    body: 'Change one value and it carries across every file that references it. The boring, easy-to-get-wrong step is the one the agent is best at.',
  },
  {
    title: 'A product, not a chat log',
    body: 'Schematic, board, gerbers and drill, DXF and STEP, renders, an orderable BOM, a firmware scaffold, and a bring-up plan. All on disk, in your repo.',
  },
  {
    title: 'Open because it has to be',
    body: 'Apache-2.0, on an open stack. Everything it writes is plain markdown and JSON in your own repository. No proprietary formats, no lock-in.',
    // the only card that earns a link: the claim is checkable
    link: { label: 'KiCad', href: links.kicad },
  },
];
---

<section id="features">
  <div class="wrap">
    <h2 class="section-title">A loop, not a chatbot.</h2>
    <p class="section-intro">
      It looks a lot like pair programming, except the codebase is a circuit
      board.
    </p>

    <ul class="grid">
      {
        features.map((f) => (
          <li class="card">
            <h3>{f.title}</h3>
            <p>{f.body}</p>
            {f.link && (
              <p class="more">
                Built on <a href={f.link.href}>{f.link.label}</a> and{' '}
                <a href={links.openspec}>OpenSpec</a>.
              </p>
            )}
          </li>
        ))
      }
    </ul>

    <p class="footnote">
      The draft layout is correct, not optimal, and says so itself.{' '}
      <code>LAYOUT.md</code> lists exactly what is solid and what a specialist
      should redo before fab. Non-optimal is acceptable. Unlabeled non-optimal is
      not.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

<style>
  .grid {
    list-style: none;
    margin: 3.25rem 0 0;
    padding: 0;
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);
    gap: 1px;
    /* hairline gutters read as a grid of cells rather than floating cards */
    background: var(--hairline);
    border: 1px solid var(--hairline);
    border-radius: 4px;
    overflow: hidden;
  }

  .card {
    background: var(--bg);
    padding: 30px 28px 32px;
  }

  .card h3 {
    font-size: 1.06rem;
  }

  .card p {
    color: var(--text-dim);
    font-size: 0.94rem;
    line-height: 1.6;
    margin: 0.75rem 0 0;
  }

  .card .more {
    font-size: 0.88rem;
  }

  .footnote {
    margin: 2.25rem 0 0;
    color: var(--text-dim);
    font-size: 0.88rem;
    line-height: 1.6;
    max-width: 62ch;
  }

  .footnote code {
    font-size: 0.82rem;
    color: var(--text);
  }

  @media (max-width: 940px) {
    .grid {
      grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr);
    }
  }

  @media (max-width: 620px) {
    .grid {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }

    .card {
      padding: 24px 20px 26px;
    }
  }
</style>
